Problem:- Decode String

Given an encoded string, return its decoded string.
The encoding rule is: k[encoded_string], where the encoded_string inside the square brackets is being repeated exactly k times. Note that k is guaranteed to be a positive integer.
You may assume that the input string is always valid; there are no extra white spaces, square brackets are well-formed, etc. Furthermore, you may assume that the original data does not contain any digits and that digits are only for those repeat numbers, k. For example, there will not be input like 3a or 2[4].
The test cases are generated so that the length of the output will never exceed 105.

Example 1:

Input: s = "3[a]2[bc]"
Output: "aaabcbc"

solutions:-

Decode String decodes nested bracket strings using stack. Classic string parsing with numbers.

#Java Implementation (Stack)

class Solution {
    public String decodeString(String s) {
        Stack<Integer> countStack = new Stack<>();
        Stack<StringBuilder> stringStack = new Stack<>();
        StringBuilder current = new StringBuilder();
        int k = 0;
        
        for (char ch : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isDigit(ch)) {
                k = k * 10 + (ch - '0');  // Multi-digit numbers
            }
            else if (ch == '[') {
                // Save current state
                countStack.push(k);
                stringStack.push(current);
                current = new StringBuilder();  // New string for inside []
                k = 0;
            }
            else if (ch == ']') {
                // Repeat and append
                StringBuilder prev = stringStack.pop();
                int times = countStack.pop();
                StringBuilder temp = new StringBuilder();
                for (int i = 0; i < times; i++) {
                    temp.append(current);
                }
                current = prev.append(temp);
            }
            else {  // Letter
                current.append(ch);
            }
        }
        return current.toString();
    }
}

Two stacks: Numbers + strings. Handle nested brackets.

#Step-by-Step Logic
Two Stacks: countStack (numbers), stringStack (strings before k[)

Process chars:
Digit: Build k (multi-digit support)
[: Push k + current string, start new string
]: Pop k + prev string, repeat, append
Letter: Add to current
Trace: "3[a]2[bc]"

text
3: k=3
[: push 3,"", current="a"
a: current="a"  
]: temp="aaa", current=""+"aaa"="aaa"
2: k=2
[: push 2,"aaa", current="b"
b: current="b"
c: current="bc"
]: temp="bcbc", current="aaa"+"bcbc"="aaabcbc" ✓

#Thought Process
Key insight: Nested structure → Stack

text
3[2[a]] = 3 × (2 × "a") = "aaaaaa"
Stack handles nesting naturally
Multi-digit numbers: k = k*10 + digit
State saving: Push before entering brackets

Why two stacks:

text
countStack: 3,2 (nesting levels)
stringStack: "","aaa" (parent strings)
Time: O(n × max_k), Space: O(n)

#Edge Cases
Nested: "3[a2[c]]" → "acacac"
Multi-digit: "10[a]" → 10×"a"
Single letter: "a" → "a"
Deep nesting: "2[3[a]b]" → "aaab aaab"
